{"questionId":"28543","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A satellite is launched from the surface of Earth into a circular orbit.</p>\n<p>The following data are given.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:60px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Mass of the satellite = 8.0 × 10<sup>2</sup> kg</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:60px;\">Height of the orbit above the surface of Earth = 5.0 × 10<sup>5</sup> m</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:60px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Mass of Earth = 6.0 × 10<sup>24</sup> kg</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:60px;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Radius of Earth = 6.4 × 10<sup>6</sup> m</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the kinetic energy of the satellite in orbit is about 2 × 10<sup>10</sup> J.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>orbital radius&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;«<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math> m»&nbsp;✓</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>KE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>24</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; <em><strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>10</mn></msup></math> «J»&nbsp;✓</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>Award <strong>[1] max</strong> for answers ignoring orbital height (KE = 2.5 × 10</em><sup><em>10</em></sup> J<em>).</em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"28543","referenceCode":"22N.2.HL.TZ0.8b.i","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Show that the kinetic energy of the satellite in orbit is about 2 × 1010 J.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields","10.2 – Fields at work","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}